            <pb n="1"/>
            <p>
                <add>Hebrew</add>
            </p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p rend="align(right)"><placeName>St. Louis</placeName>, <date>June 6, 1862</date>.</p>
            <p><addressee>Rev. Isaac Leeser</addressee>, <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>,</p>
            <p>Honored Sir:</p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">Along with the hope that my letter may find you in the best<lb/> of
                health, I am sending you herewith $15. for books sold. Have the good-<lb/>ness to
                send me 3 or 4 dozen of the Hebrew readers. Send it by express.<lb/> It has been
                impossible for me, until now, to collect anything either for<lb/> your paper or for
                that of <persName>Wise</persName> or <persName>Isaacs</persName>. Times are very bad
                here.<lb/> People barely have enough for necessities, so bad is business. There
                is<lb/> no news. That is why I want to close with the question whether you have<lb/>
                received my $15. As soon as times change I shall collect once more. You<lb/> have my
                last letter with the $15. which has remained unanswered now for<lb/> a long time. In
                my German congregation I have peace, thank God, and hope<lb/> that the situation
                will remain so. The beginning has been made, and the<lb/> firm of <persName>Marx and
                    Schoen</persName> observe the <date>Sabbath</date> and their business is
                complete-<lb/>ly closed. Also 2 baker members of my community now observe the
                    <date>Sabbath</date>.<lb/> In time I hope that others will do so. On
                    <date>Shabuoth</date>, the son of <persName>L. R. Straus</persName><lb/> became
                Bar-Mitzvah, as well as 3 other boys who did me honor, since, as<lb/> you know, my
                congregation is purely German, everything was conducted in<lb/> the German language,
                except for the religious questions which I taught<lb/> out of your valuable book. It
                is possible that <persName>Mr. Straus</persName> will write to<lb/> you about
                it.</p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">Wishing you constant health,</p>
            <p rend="indent(7)">Your devoted</p>
            <p rend="indent(9)">
                <persName role="author">M. Kuttner</persName>
            </p>
        </body>
